post_text: WHS Cross Country runners will be doing a "Virtual" meet tomorrow Saturday, September 12th starting at 10:00 AM. They will be starting and finishing on the road leading to the nature trail. If you have the time, come out and cheer them on to give them some incentive to run their best! If you plan on attending, please wear a face covering and social distance from those not in your household. Being able to follow protocol and doing what is best for our athletes will help ensure our programs get to continue. The Girls race will start at 10:00 am and the boys will start approximately 30 minutes later. See you there!

post_text:
Just a reminder, tomorrow Tuesday, September 8 is the first day of school! Evergreen Elementary doors will open at 7:55 am. Wrangell High and Stikine Middle Schools doors will open at 7:50 (with the exception of zero hour WHS class at 7:30 am).

Wrangell High students can enter either through the WHS commons door next to the weight room or the upstairs door by the office. Stikine Middle School students need to enter through the SMS Commons door. Evergreen Elementary students grades 2-5 enter through the back door of the gym and grades K-1 enter at the south end of the building. Please be prepared for screening upon entry.

Remember to wear your masks and bring a water bottle and sweater as windows will be open for increased air circulation.

We are so excited to see all of you!! Here‚Äôs to a great 2020 - 2021 school year!

post_text:
As of today (Thursday, Sept. 3, 2020), taking into account our current staffing model, student enrollment numbers, and mitigation plan, Wrangell Public Schools will open Evergreen Elementary, Stikine Middle School, and Wrangell High School under a medium risk designation on Tuesday, Sept. 8. Delivery methods for medium risk are outlined in the district's Smart Start plan.

Wrangell Public Schools staff appreciates your continued patience and cooperation as we work to ensure a safe learning environment. The plan, and subsequent risk factor assignment, will remain fluid as information emerges about mitigating COVID-19, its presence within the community, and the necessary local response.

WE JUST CANNOT WAIT!!!!

Teachers and staff wanted to have a little pre-first day of school fun and see our registered students! We‚Äôve missed everyone soooooo much since the Spring closure and summer break!

So, we have planned a welcome drive-by celebration on Monday, August 24th. See the flyer for the drive by schedule. üòÄ

Teachers and staff will be waiting to give a big hello and a wave. Welcome bags are being assembled to introduce EES grade-leveled teaching teams, generic supply lists will be included, as well as some fun treats. Best of all, because you are all ‚Äúotterly‚Äù amazing, we will have mini otter pops to hand out! What‚Äôs summer without otter pops???

Be sure to register by Friday, August 21 to get on the list for the drive by welcome bag pick up celebration on Monday, August 24. We don‚Äôt want to miss anyone!

Here is to the start of a great 2020-2021 School Year. It may look different, but we are working hard to make it the best it can be!

post_text:
This was just released. Our updates will be posted by Friday.

The goal of the 2020-2021 school year is to ensure that education and activity are the constants in students' lives, while COVID-19 is the variable. Ensuring every child has access to meaningful, safe education while keeping children, teachers, and communities healthy will be a challenge this year. Through partnership, innovation, and collaboration we will best serve our children - the whole ecosystem of the child needs to be mobilized. We encourage everyone to think of this year not as how to do more of the same - but differently, by acknowledging this school year will inherently look nothing like any school year before, and embracing the change by highlighting our community to be resilient, creative and flexible in this time of great challenge.

Thank you for your partnership.

Timeline for SMART START planning process:

Task Force meetings will be Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday. The meeting Friday will include members from the EOC. At the meeting on Friday, the EOC will review our district start up plan.

We will make fine or small revisions to our plan until Monday, July 27.

At that time, we will post our plan on our district web site under the SMART START tab.

Our team has worked hard to consider all options brought to our attention and our plans will be based on our full compliment of resources available.

As a reminder, please use the email address smartstart@wpsd.us for any questions, comments, or concerns.

post_text:
Free COVID-19 Testing available this weekend!

Good morning WPS team!

In case you were unable to hear the announcement the other night at the Town Hall meeting, our community is offering free testing for COVID-19. The hours for the free testing are 10-4 on Saturday and Sunday only. Free testing will continue each weekend until the end of December. They health team lets you self swab if you prefer. It truly only takes a moment for the test. The testing center is located near the new hospital construction site by the clinic.

Michael and I will be tested today. I think it is important for our team to know if we have the infection and are asymptomatic. I encourage you to bring your families as well. Children can learn how and why it is done.

Thank you for your consideration in this important matter.

Debbe Lancaster
Superintendent - WPS

The Superintendent of Schools is generally evaluated twice per year: a formative evaluation in the fall and a summative evaluation in the spring, Prior to the summative evaluation, the Board will solicit input on the performance of the superintendent from the public at-large; in similar fashion to the way input is collected for teacher and administrator evaluation.

Please take a moment to comment on the Superintendent's performance. You can request a form from Mrs. Kim Powell at 907-874-2347 or kpowell@wpsd.us or submit a letter to:

Aaron Angerman, President

Wrangell Public School Board

P.O. Box 2319

Wrangell, AK 99929-2319

post_text: Evergreen Elementary School is hosting an end of the school year celebration at the EES Playground starting at 1 pm on Thursday, May 21st. Parents please head down Spur Road and approach EES by driving down the side road past the ball field (first right off of Spur). Drop off one student at a time (or family from the same household) at the playground door closest to the ball field. They will do a celebration walk/dance through a path of staff all the way over to the other end of the playground door (near Mr. Merritt's classroom), where their ride will pick them up after they are treated to a cupcake. Dress up CRAZY if you wish to! All other family members must remain in the car. Please keep the vehicles moving up to the wait points. There will be signs up to direct traffic. If students are walking to the celebration they must be with an adult. If you have any questions please call the office at 907-874-2321.

We are full of gratitude and amazed at the generosity of our communities during COVID-19. Thank you for your donations, support and for your recognition of our providers and staff on the front lines. A special thank you to Wrangell Public Schools for this video!

We'd also like to thank Native Roots Alaskan Boutique, Angerman's Inc. and the City of Ketchikan for your donations to Wrangell Medical Center.

And, thank you to Wrangell community members donating and making face masks, buttons, headbands and shields, including Marilyn Mork, Kevin and Moira FIsh, Drew Larrabee, Christy Haslip, Nola Walker, Carol Hay and Phyllis Daniels.

NEWS RELEASE
For immediate release: 03/26/2020 3:15 p.m.

COVID-19 UPDATE: RESPONSE BY THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION

TO REQUESTS FOR LOCAL AIRPORT CLOSURES

Wrangell, AK ‚Äì Many Wrangell residents have asked if the City & Borough of Wrangell (CBW) can mandate closure of the airport as a way to prevent further risk of COVD-19 being introduced to the community by an incoming passenger. The CBW does not own, nor does it have the authority to close the airport terminal (owned and operated by Alaska Airlines), or the airport runway (owned and operated by the Alaska Department of Transportation & Public Facilities).

Recently, the Alaska Department of Transportation issued the attached letter explaining why the Department will not be closing any airports due to the COVID-19 Pandemic.

##

Contact: Wrangell Borough Clerk, 907.874.2381, clerk@wrangell.com

Effective immediately, Jack Carney will be the principal for Stikine Middle School and Wrangell High School.

Please forward all questions, comments, and concerns to him from this point forward. He will be working in PLC groups, assisting staff during our online education process for grades 6-12, and working with parents to coordinate graduation for our seniors.

Megan Powell will also be helpful with this transition during our unprecedented times. We will work together to try and make this as smooth as possible.

Thank you for your continued support as we move forward.

post_text: Congratulations, EES!
shared_text:
Debbe Lancaster is with Mikki Angerman and 2 others.
February 5 at 7:55 AM ¬∑

Our Evergreen Elementary staff has worked as a team for many years. Because of their collaborative efforts and teamwork, they have increased student achievement through increasing literacy, closing achievement gaps, and providing support to all students through Title IA funded opportunities.

The staff is being recognized in Atlanta today for their hard work and strong leadership in the battle for improving literacy in their school. I am proud that we sent the building administrator, two teachers, and two paraprofessionals to accept the EES award. There are only 2 schools from each state chosen to attend this national recognition ceremony.

They have plenty of reason to be super proud. When I spoke with the administrator a few minutes ago, she said they are "on fire" validation from others that they are doing many best practices. They also said they are getting many more new ideas to bring back for all of us. They are with the best of the best.

post_text:
*Announcement*

Public Hearing Meeting tonight at 6:30 EES Room 101

The public is invited to comment on what is important to consider when developing the SY 2020-2021 budget. We are meeting to collect input and looking for a list of community priorities. Please share your thoughts to include strategic ways to fund your priorities.

Our focus will not be on cutting other programs but rather a collaborative time to strategize about the best education experience possible for all of our students.

Tonight's meeting will include an explanation of budget development. The WPSD Strategic Plan frames budget allocations based on stakeholder input. Please follow this link to our Strategic Plan for more information on our district goals.

https://www.wpsd.us/domain/196

Everyone is welcome. It is important to hear your voice!

post_text: Evergreen Elementary School and Wrangell Public Schools is excited to announce that Mrs. Miller-Yancey has received the Patriotic Award Citation for her support for the National Guard and in supporting Mr. Matt Nore and his family during his active duty. Along with this award Evergreen Elementary School and Wrangell School district have been recognized for their Military support as well. We thank Mr. Nore for his service along with all the men and women in the Military.
